entry.title: Special Weather Statement issued March 20 at 3:58PM EDT by NWS Mount Holly NJ
entry.summary:
Gusty winds along with rain and snow showers will continue to affect the area through early this evening. There will also be the continuing threat of a few heavier snow squalls which could quickly reduce visibility to near zero in blowing snow making travel dangerous. The highest threat for these squalls will be for areas near and north of the I-80 corridor. In addition, squalls could bring winds gusting over 50 mph adding to further travel challenges.
Be alert for rapidly changing conditions. If you are traveling today and receive a Snow Squall Warning, use extra caution, reduce speed, and leave extra space between you and the vehicle in front of you. Be alert for sudden whiteout conditions and get off on the nearest exit or avoid travel until the squall passes.

entry.title: Hydrologic Outlook issued March 20 at 3:45PM EDT by NWS Miami FL
entry.summary:
ESFMFL
A surface low is forecast to develop over the Gulf of Mexico sometime on Friday and move eastward across portions of the Florida Peninsula Friday night into Saturday morning. This will allow for a warm front to move through South Florida on Friday afternoon into Friday evening before a cold front moves southward through the area Saturday morning. This will lead to couple of rounds of rains and thunderstorms over South Florida during this time frame.
The forecast soundings are also showing that the precipitable water values will be around 1.6 to 1.8 inches which is above the 90th percentile and near the maximum values for this time of year. This means that heavy rainfall is also possible with the rounds of showers and thunderstorms. At this time it looks rainfall totals of 3 to 5 inches are possible with locally higher amounts possible with any training of thunderstorms.
The ground across South Florida is somewhat dry due to the lack of rainfall the last couple of weeks. However, with the locally heavy rainfall there could be some isolated areas of flooding with the showers and thunderstorms, especially where the thunderstorms train over the same area.

Please exercise caution if handling open flames or equipment that creates sparks. Dispose of cigarette buttes, matches, and other flammable materials in appropriate containers. Keep vehicles off of dry grass and obey local burn bans. Most dry grasses, dead leaves, and other tree litter could easily ignite and spread fire quickly.

entry.title: Special Weather Statement issued March 20 at 3:50AM EDT by NWS Jackson KY
entry.summary:
An enhanced risk of erratic fire behavior will occur today, as relative humidity lowers to between 25 and 30 percent, along with winds of 15 to 25 mph switching from southwest to northwest as a dry cold front moves through the area. Some locations near I-64 could see isolated wind gusts above 30 mph in the afternoon.
Please refer to your local burn permitting authorities on whether you can burn today. Use caution when burning as fires may get out of hand quickly in these conditions.
Another shot of cold air will send temperatures to well below freezing at most locations tonight. With forecast lows in the low to mid 20s for the valleys and mid to upper 20s on the ridges, any freshly budding or blossoming vegetation could be damaged or killed. Now is the time to prepare for this cold snap.
